  "text": "PSO algorithm, different from the genetic algorithm etc., is evolved by the cooperation and competition among individuals but not genetic operators. In the stage of evolution, PSO has many advantages, especially its excellent global optimization ability, simple operation and easy implementation, no selection, crossover, mutation and so on. In order to further improve the global optimization ability of PSO. This paper introduces a modified PSO using dynamically decreasing inertia weight [CITATION_1] . As mentioned by Shi and Eberhart, when the inertia weight is low ( ≤ 0.8), the search time is very short, that is, all the particles tend to gather together quickly. This confirms that the PSO is more like a local search algorithm when is small. If there is an acceptable solution within the initial search space, then the PSO will find the global optimum quickly, otherwise it will not find the global optimum. On the contrary, when the inertia weight is large ( ≥ 1.2), the PSO algorithm always explores new regions. Of course, the PSO algorithm needs more iteration to reach the global optimal, and it is more likely not to find the global optimal. When the inertia weight is moderate (0.8 < < 1.2), the PSO will have the best chance to find the global optimum but also takes a moderate number of iterations. According to these analyses, Shi and Eberhart do not set the inertia weight as the fixed value, but set it to a function that decreases linearly with time, and the function of the inertia weight is:",
